B044C013V006	44	13	6	They went through the whole island as far as Paphos, where they found a Jewish occult practitioner and false prophet named Bar-Jesus.
B044C013V007	44	13	7	He was associated with the proconsul Sergius Paulus, who was an intelligent man. He sent for Barnabas and Saul because he wanted to hear the word of God.
B044C013V008	44	13	8	But Elymas the occult practitioner (that is the meaning of his name) continued to oppose them and tried to turn the proconsul away from the faith.
B044C013V009	44	13	9	But Saul, also known as Paul, filled with the Holy Spirit, looked him straight in the eye
B044C013V010	44	13	10	and said, “You are full of every form of deception and trickery, you son of the devil, you enemy of all that is right! You will never stop perverting the straight ways of the Lord, will you?
B044C013V011	44	13	11	The hand of the Lord is against you now, and you will be blind and not see the sun for a while!” At that moment a dark mist came over him, and he went around looking for someone to lead him by the hand.
B044C013V012	44	13	12	When the proconsul saw what had happened, he believed, for he was astonished at the Lord's teaching.
B044C013V013	44	13	13	Then Paul and his men set sail from Paphos and arrived in Perga in Pamphylia. But John left them and went back to Jerusalem.
B044C013V014	44	13	14	They left Perga and arrived in Antioch in Pisidia. On the Sabbath day they went into the synagogue and sat down.
B044C013V015	44	13	15	After the reading of the Law and the Prophets, the synagogue leaders asked them, “Brothers, if you have any message of encouragement for the people, you may speak.”
B044C013V016	44	13	16	Then Paul stood up, motioned with his hand, and said: “Men of Israel and you who fear God, listen!
B044C013V017	44	13	17	The God of this people Israel chose our ancestors and made them a great people during their stay in the land of Egypt, and with an uplifted arm he led them out of it.
B044C013V018	44	13	18	After he had put up with them for forty years in the wilderness,
B044C013V019	44	13	19	he destroyed seven nations in the land of Canaan. Then he gave them their land as an inheritance
B044C013V020	44	13	20	for about 450 years. After that he gave them judges until the time of the prophet Samuel.
B044C013V021	44	13	21	“Then they demanded a king, and for forty years God gave them Saul, the son of Kish, a man of the tribe of Benjamin.
B044C013V022	44	13	22	But he removed Saul and made David their king, about whom he testified, ‘I have found that David, the son of Jesse, is a man after my own heart, who will carry out all my wishes.’
B044C013V023	44	13	23	It was from this man's descendants that God, as he promised, brought to Israel a Savior, who is Jesus.
B044C013V024	44	13	24	Before his coming, John had already preached a baptism of repentance to all the people in Israel.
B044C013V025	44	13	25	When John was finishing his work, he said, ‘Who do you think I am? I am not the one. No, but he is coming after me, and I am not worthy to untie the sandals on his feet.’
B044C013V026	44	13	26	“My brothers, descendants of Abraham's family, and those among you who fear God, it is to us that the message of this salvation has been sent.
B044C013V027	44	13	27	For the people who live in Jerusalem and their leaders, not knowing who he was, condemned him and fulfilled the words of the prophets that are read every Sabbath.
B044C013V028	44	13	28	Although they found no reason to sentence him to death, they asked Pilate to have him executed.
B044C013V029	44	13	29	When they had finished doing everything that was written about him, they took him down from the tree and placed him in a tomb.
B044C013V030	44	13	30	But God raised him from the dead,
B044C013V031	44	13	31	and for many days he appeared to those who had come with him to Jerusalem from Galilee. These are now his witnesses to the people.
B044C013V032	44	13	32	We are telling you the good news: What God promised our ancestors
B044C013V033	44	13	33	he has fulfilled for us, their descendants, by raising Jesus. As it is written in the second Psalm, ‘You are my Son. Today I have become your Father.’
B044C013V034	44	13	34	He raised him from the dead, never to experience decay. As he said, ‘I will give you the holy promises made to David.’
B044C013V035	44	13	35	In another Psalm he says, ‘You will not let your Holy One experience decay.’
B044C013V036	44	13	36	For David, after he had served God's purpose in his own generation, died and was laid to rest with his ancestors, and so he experienced decay.
B044C013V037	44	13	37	However, the man whom God raised did not experience decay.
B044C013V038	44	13	38	“Therefore, brothers, you must understand that through him the forgiveness of sins is proclaimed to you,
B044C013V039	44	13	39	and that everyone who believes in him is justified and freed from everything that kept you from being justified by the law of Moses.
B044C013V040	44	13	40	So be careful that what the prophets said does not happen to you:
B044C013V041	44	13	41	‘Look, you mockers!Be amazed and die!	For I am doing a work in your days, a work that you would not believeeven if someone told you!’”
B044C013V042	44	13	42	As Paul and Barnabas were leaving, the people kept urging them to tell them the same things the next Sabbath.
B044C013V043	44	13	43	When the meeting of the synagogue broke up, many Jews and devout converts to Judaism followed Paul and Barnabas, who kept talking to them and urging them to continue in the grace of God.
B044C013V044	44	13	44	The next Sabbath almost the whole town gathered to hear the word of the Lord.
B044C013V045	44	13	45	But when the Jews saw the crowds, they were filled with jealousy and began to object to the statements made by Paul and even to abuse him.
B044C013V046	44	13	46	Then Paul and Barnabas boldly declared, “We had to speak God's word to you first, but since you reject it and consider yourselves unworthy of eternal life, we are now going to turn to the Gentiles.
B044C013V047	44	13	47	For that is what the Lord ordered us to do: ‘I have made you a light to the Gentiles to be the means of salvation to the very ends of the earth.’”
B044C013V048	44	13	48	When the Gentiles heard this, they began rejoicing and glorifying the word of the Lord. Meanwhile, all who had been destined to eternal life believed,
B044C013V049	44	13	49	and the word of the Lord began to spread throughout the whole region.
B044C013V050	44	13	50	But the Jews stirred up devout women of high social standing and the officials in the city, started a persecution against Paul and Barnabas, and drove them out of their territory.
B044C013V051	44	13	51	So they shook the dust off their feet in protest against them and went to Iconium.
B044C013V052	44	13	52	Meanwhile, the disciples continued to be full of joy and of the Holy Spirit.
B044C014V001	44	14	1	In Iconium they went into the Jewish synagogue and spoke in such a way that a great number of both Jews and Greeks believed.
B044C014V002	44	14	2	But the Jews who refused to believe stirred up the Gentiles and poisoned their minds against the brothers.
B044C014V003	44	14	3	They stayed there a considerable time and continued to speak boldly for the Lord, who kept affirming his word of grace and granting signs and wonders to be done by them.
B044C014V004	44	14	4	But the people of the city were divided. Some were with the Jews, while others were with the apostles.
B044C014V005	44	14	5	Now when an attempt was made by both Gentiles and Jews, along with their authorities, to mistreat and stone them,
B044C014V006	44	14	6	they found out about it and fled to the Lycaonian towns of Lystra and Derbe and to the surrounding territory.
B044C014V007	44	14	7	There they kept telling the good news.
B044C014V008	44	14	8	Now in Lystra there was a man sitting down who couldn't use his feet. He had been crippled from birth and had never walked.
B044C014V009	44	14	9	He was listening to Paul as he spoke. Paul watched him closely, and when he saw that he had faith to be healed,
B044C014V010	44	14	10	he said in a loud voice, “Stand up straight on your feet!” Then the man jumped up and began to walk.
B044C014V011	44	14	11	When the crowds saw what Paul had done, they shouted in the Lycaonian language, “The gods have become like men and have come down to us!”
B044C014V012	44	14	12	They began to call Barnabas Zeus, and Paul Hermes, because he was the main speaker.
B044C014V013	44	14	13	The priest of the temple of Zeus, which was just outside the city, brought bulls and garlands to the gates. He and the crowds wanted to offer sacrifices.
B044C014V014	44	14	14	But when the apostles Barnabas and Paul heard of it, they tore their clothes and rushed out into the crowd, shouting,
B044C014V015	44	14	15	“Men, why are you doing this? We are merely human beings with natures like your own. We are telling you the good news to turn from these worthless things to the living God, who made heaven and earth, the sea, and everything in them.
B044C014V016	44	14	16	In past generations he allowed all the nations to go their own ways,
B044C014V017	44	14	17	yet he has not left himself without a witness by doing good, by giving you rain from heaven and fruitful seasons, and by filling you with food and joyful hearts.”
B044C014V018	44	14	18	Even by saying this it was all they could do to keep the crowds from offering sacrifices to them.
B044C014V019	44	14	19	But some Jews came from Antioch and Iconium and won the crowds by persuasion. They stoned Paul and dragged him out of the town, thinking he was dead.
B044C014V020	44	14	20	But the disciples formed a circle around him, and he got up and went back to town. The next day he went on with Barnabas to Derbe.
B044C014V021	44	14	21	As they were proclaiming the good news in that city, they discipled a large number of people. Then they went back to Lystra, Iconium, and Antioch,
B044C014V022	44	14	22	strengthening the souls of the disciples and encouraging them to continue in the faith, saying, “We must endure many hardships to get into the kingdom of God.”
B044C014V023	44	14	23	They appointed elders for them in each church, and with prayer and fasting they entrusted them to the Lord in whom they had believed.
B044C014V024	44	14	24	Then they passed through Pisidia and came to Pamphylia.
B044C014V025	44	14	25	They spoke the word in Perga and went down to Attalia.
B044C014V026	44	14	26	From there they sailed back to Antioch, where they had been commended to the grace of God for the work they had completed.
B044C014V027	44	14	27	When they arrived, they called the church together and told them everything that God had done with them and how he had opened a door of faith to the Gentiles.
B044C014V028	44	14	28	Then they spent a long time with the disciples.
B044C015V001	44	15	1	Then some men came down from Judea and started to teach the brothers, “Unless you are circumcised according to the law of Moses, you can't be saved.”
B044C015V002	44	15	2	Paul and Barnabas had quite a dispute and argument with them. So Paul and Barnabas and some of the others were appointed to go up to Jerusalem to confer with the apostles and elders about this question.
B044C015V003	44	15	3	They were sent on their way by the church, and as they were going through Phoenecia and Samaria they told of the conversion of the Gentiles and brought great joy to all the brothers.
B044C015V004	44	15	4	When they arrived in Jerusalem, they were welcomed by the church, the apostles, and the elders, and they reported everything that God had done through them.
B044C015V005	44	15	5	But some believers from the party of the Pharisees stood up and said, “They must be circumcised and ordered to keep the law of Moses.”
B044C015V006	44	15	6	So the apostles and the elders met to consider this statement.
B044C015V007	44	15	7	After a lengthy debate, Peter stood up and said to them, “Brothers, you know that in the early days God chose me to be the one among you through whom the Gentiles would hear the message of the gospel and believe.
B044C015V008	44	15	8	God, who knows everyone's heart, showed them he approved by giving them the Holy Spirit, just as he did to us.
B044C015V009	44	15	9	He made no distinction between them and us, because he cleansed their hearts by faith.
B044C015V010	44	15	10	So why do you test God by putting on the disciples’ neck a yoke that neither our ancestors nor we could carry?
B044C015V011	44	15	11	We certainly believe that it is through the grace of the Lord Jesus Christ that we are saved, just as they are.”
B044C015V012	44	15	12	The whole crowd was silent as they listened to Barnabas and Paul tell about all the signs and wonders that God had done through them among the Gentiles.
B044C015V013	44	15	13	After they had finished speaking, James responded by saying, “Brothers, listen to me.
B044C015V014	44	15	14	Simeon has explained how God first showed his concern for the Gentiles by taking from among them a people for his name.
B044C015V015	44	15	15	This agrees with the words of the prophets. As it is written,
B044C015V016	44	15	16	‘After this, I will come backand set up David's fallen tent again.	I will restore its ruined places and set it up again
B044C015V017	44	15	17	so that the rest of the people may search for the Lord,			including all the Gentiles who are called by my name,	declares the Lord.	He is the one who has been doing these things
B044C015V018	44	15	18	that have always been known.’
B044C015V019	44	15	19	Therefore, I have decided that we should not trouble these Gentiles who are turning to God.
B044C015V020	44	15	20	Instead, we should write to them to keep away from things polluted by idols, from sexual immorality, from anything strangled, and from blood.
B044C015V021	44	15	21	After all, Moses has had people to proclaim him in every city for generations, and on every Sabbath he is read aloud in the synagogues.”
B044C015V022	44	15	22	Then the apostles, the elders, and the whole church decided to choose some of their men to send with Paul and Barnabas to Antioch. These were Judas, who was called Barsabbas, and Silas, who were leaders among the brothers.
B044C015V023	44	15	23	They wrote this letter for them to deliver:“From the apostles and the elders, your brothers, to their Gentile brothers in Antioch, Syria, and Cilicia. Greetings.
B044C015V024	44	15	24	We have heard that some men, coming from us without instructions from us, have said things to trouble you and have unsettled your minds.
B044C015V025	44	15	25	So we have unanimously decided to choose men and send them to you with our dear Barnabas and Paul,
B044C015V026	44	15	26	who have risked their lives for the sake of our Lord Jesus Christ.
B044C015V027	44	15	27	We have therefore sent Judas and Silas to tell you the same things by word of mouth.
B044C015V028	44	15	28	For it seemed good to the Holy Spirit and to us not to place on you any burden but these essential requirements:
B044C015V029	44	15	29	to keep away from food sacrificed to idols, from blood, from anything strangled, and from sexual immorality. If you avoid these things, you will prosper. Goodbye.”
B044C015V030	44	15	30	So the men were sent on their way and arrived in Antioch. They gathered the congregation together and delivered the letter.
B044C015V031	44	15	31	When the people read it, they were pleased with the encouragement it brought them.
B044C015V032	44	15	32	Then Judas and Silas, who were also prophets, said much to encourage and strengthen the brothers.
B044C015V033	44	15	33	After staying there for some time, they were sent back with a greeting from the brothers to those who had sent them.
B044C015V035	44	15	35	Both Paul and Barnabas stayed in Antioch and taught and proclaimed the word of the Lord, as did many others.
B044C015V036	44	15	36	Some days after this, Paul said to Barnabas, “Let's go back and visit the brothers in every town where we proclaimed the word of the Lord and see how they're doing.”
B044C015V037	44	15	37	Barnabas persisted in wanting to take along John, who was called Mark,
B044C015V038	44	15	38	but Paul did not think it was right to be taking along the man who had deserted them in Pamphylia and had not gone with them into the work.
B044C015V039	44	15	39	The disagreement was so sharp that they parted ways. Barnabas took Mark and sailed to Cyprus,
B044C015V040	44	15	40	while Paul chose Silas and left after the brothers had commended him to the grace of the Lord.
B044C015V041	44	15	41	He went through Syria and Cilicia and strengthened the churches.
B044C016V001	44	16	1	He also went to Derbe and Lystra. Here there was a disciple named Timothy, the son of a Jewish woman who was a believer, although his father was a Greek.
B044C016V002	44	16	2	He was highly regarded by the brothers in Lystra and Iconium.
B044C016V003	44	16	3	Paul wanted this man to go with him, so he took him and had him circumcised because of the Jews who lived in those places, for everyone knew that his father was a Greek.
B044C016V004	44	16	4	As they went from town to town, they delivered the decisions reached by the apostles and elders in Jerusalem for them to obey.
B044C016V005	44	16	5	So the churches continued to be strengthened in the faith and to increase in numbers every day.
B044C016V006	44	16	6	Then they went through the region of Phrygia and Galatia because they had been prevented by the Holy Spirit from speaking the word in Asia.
B044C016V007	44	16	7	They went as far as Mysia and tried to enter Bithynia, but the Spirit of Jesus did not let them.
B044C016V008	44	16	8	So they passed by Mysia and went down to Troas.
B044C016V009	44	16	9	During the night Paul had a vision. A man from Macedonia was standing there and pleading with him, “Come over to Macedonia and help us!”
B044C016V010	44	16	10	As soon as he had seen the vision, we immediately looked for a way to go to Macedonia, for we were convinced that God had called us to tell them the good news.
B044C016V011	44	16	11	Sailing from Troas, we went straight to Samothrace, the next day to Neapolis,
B044C016V012	44	16	12	and from there to Philippi, a leading city of the district of Macedonia and a Roman colony. We were in this city for several days.
B044C016V013	44	16	13	On the Sabbath day we went out of the gate and along the river, where we thought there was a place of prayer. We sat down and began talking to the women who had gathered there.
B044C016V014	44	16	14	A woman named Lydia, a dealer in purple goods from the city of Thyatira, was listening to us. She was a worshiper of God, and the Lord opened her heart to listen carefully to what was being said by Paul.
B044C016V015	44	16	15	When she and her family were baptized, she urged us, “If you are convinced that I am a believer in the Lord, come and stay at my home.” And she continued to insist that we do so.
B044C016V016	44	16	16	Once, as we were going to the place of prayer, we met a slave girl who had a spirit of fortune-telling and who had brought her owners a great deal of money by predicting the future.
B044C016V017	44	16	17	She would follow Paul and us and shout, “These men are servants of the Most High God and are proclaiming to you a way of salvation!”
B044C016V018	44	16	18	She kept doing this for many days until Paul became annoyed, turned to the spirit, and said, “I command you in the name of Jesus Christ to come out of her!” And it came out that very moment.
B044C016V019	44	16	19	When her owners realized that their hope of making money was gone, they grabbed Paul and Silas and dragged them before the authorities in the public square.
B044C016V020	44	16	20	They brought them before the magistrates and said, “These men are stirring up a lot of trouble in our city. They are Jews
B044C016V021	44	16	21	and are advocating customs that we are not allowed to accept or practice as Romans.”
B044C016V022	44	16	22	The crowd joined in the attack against them. Then the magistrates had them stripped of their clothes and ordered them beaten with sticks.
B044C016V023	44	16	23	After giving them a severe beating, they threw them in jail and ordered the jailer to keep them under tight security.
B044C016V024	44	16	24	Having received these orders, he put them into the inner cell and fastened their feet in leg irons.
B044C016V025	44	16	25	Around midnight, Paul and Silas were praying and singing hymns to God, and the other prisoners were listening to them.
B044C016V026	44	16	26	Suddenly, there was an earthquake so violent that the foundations of the prison were shaken. All the doors immediately flew open, and everyone's chains were unfastened.
B044C016V027	44	16	27	When the jailer woke up and saw the prison doors wide open, he drew his sword and was about to kill himself, for he thought the prisoners had escaped.
B044C016V028	44	16	28	But Paul shouted in a loud voice, “Don't hurt yourself, for we are all here!”
B044C016V029	44	16	29	The jailer asked for torches and rushed inside. He was trembling as he knelt in front of Paul and Silas.
B044C016V030	44	16	30	Then he took them outside and asked, “Sirs, what must I do to be saved?”
B044C016V031	44	16	31	They answered, “Believe on the Lord Jesus, and you and your family will be saved.”
B044C016V032	44	16	32	Then they spoke the word of the Lord to him and everyone in his home.
B044C016V033	44	16	33	At that hour of the night he took them and washed their wounds. Then he and his entire family were baptized immediately.
B044C016V034	44	16	34	He brought them upstairs into his house and set food before them, and he and everyone in his house were thrilled to be believers in God.
B044C016V035	44	16	35	When day came, the magistrates sent guards and said, “Release those men.”
B044C016V036	44	16	36	The jailer reported these words to Paul, saying, “The magistrates have sent word to release you. So come out now and go in peace.”
B044C016V037	44	16	37	But Paul told them, “They have had us beaten publicly without a trial and have thrown us into jail, even though we are Roman citizens. Now are they going to throw us out secretly? Certainly not! Have them come and escort us out.”
B044C016V038	44	16	38	The guards reported these words to the magistrates, and they were afraid when they heard that they were Roman citizens.
B044C016V039	44	16	39	So they came, apologized to them, and escorted them out. Then they asked them to leave the city.
B044C016V040	44	16	40	Leaving the jail, they went to Lydia's house. They saw the brothers, encouraged them, and then left.
B044C017V001	44	17	1	They traveled through Amphipolis and Apollonia and came to Thessalonica, where there was a Jewish synagogue.
B044C017V002	44	17	2	As usual, Paul went in and on three Sabbaths discussed the Scriptures with them.
B044C017V003	44	17	3	He explained and showed them that the Christ had to suffer and rise from the dead. He said, “This very Jesus whom I proclaim to you is the Christ.”
B044C017V004	44	17	4	Some of them were persuaded to join Paul and Silas, especially a large crowd of devout Greeks and the wives of many prominent men.
B044C017V005	44	17	5	But the Jews became jealous, and they took some contemptible characters who used to hang out in the public square, formed a mob, and started a riot in the city. They attacked Jason's home and searched it for Paul and Silas in order to bring them out to the people.
B044C017V006	44	17	6	When they didn't find them, they dragged Jason and some other brothers before the city officials and shouted, “These fellows who have turned the world upside down have come here, too,
B044C017V007	44	17	7	and Jason has welcomed them as his guests. All of them oppose the emperor's decrees by saying that there is another king—Jesus!”
B044C017V008	44	17	8	The crowd and the city officials were upset when they heard this,
B044C017V009	44	17	9	but after they had gotten a bond from Jason and the others they let them go.
B044C017V010	44	17	10	That night the brothers immediately sent Paul and Silas away to Berea. When they arrived, they went into the Jewish synagogue.
B044C017V011	44	17	11	These people were more receptive than those in Thessalonica. They were very willing to receive the message, and every day they carefully examined the Scriptures to see if those things were so.
B044C017V012	44	17	12	Many of them believed, including a large number of prominent Greek women and men.
B044C017V013	44	17	13	But when the Jews in Thessalonica found out that the word of God had been proclaimed by Paul also in Berea, they went there to upset and incite the crowds.
B044C017V014	44	17	14	Then the brothers immediately sent Paul away to the coast, but Silas and Timothy stayed there.
B044C017V015	44	17	15	The men who escorted Paul took him all the way to Athens and, after receiving instructions to have Silas and Timothy join him as soon as possible, they left.
B044C017V016	44	17	16	While Paul was waiting for them in Athens, his spirit was stirred to its depths to see the city full of idols.
B044C017V017	44	17	17	So he began holding discussions in the synagogue with the Jews and other worshipers, as well as every day in the public square with anyone who happened to be there.
B044C017V018	44	17	18	Some Epicurean and Stoic philosophers also debated with him. Some asked, “What is this blabbermouth trying to say?” while others said, “He seems to be preaching about foreign gods.” This was because he was telling the good news about Jesus and the resurrection.
B044C017V019	44	17	19	Then they took him, brought him before the Areopagus, and asked, “May we know what this new teaching of yours is?
B044C017V020	44	17	20	It sounds rather strange to our ears, and we would like to know what it means.”
B044C017V021	44	17	21	Now all the Athenians and the foreigners living there used to spend their time in nothing else than repeating or listening to the latest ideas.
B044C017V022	44	17	22	So Paul stood up in front of the Areopagus and said, “Men of Athens, I see that you are very religious in every way.
B044C017V023	44	17	23	For as I was walking around and looking closely at the objects you worship, I even found an altar with this written on it: ‘To an unknown god.’ So I am telling you about the unknown object you worship.
B044C017V024	44	17	24	The God who made the world and everything in it is the Lord of heaven and earth. He doesn't live in shrines made by human hands,
B044C017V025	44	17	25	and he isn't served by hands as if he needed anything. He himself gives everyone life, breath, and everything.
B044C017V026	44	17	26	From one man he made every nation of humanity to live all over the earth, fixing the seasons of the year and the boundaries they live in,
B044C017V027	44	17	27	so that they might look for God, somehow reach for him, and find him. Of course, he is never far from any one of us.
B044C017V028	44	17	28	For we live, move, and exist because of him, as some of your own poets have said: ‘For we are his children, too.’
B044C017V029	44	17	29	So if we are God's children, we shouldn't think that the divine being is like gold, silver, or stone, or is an image carved by human imagination and skill.
B044C017V030	44	17	30	Though God has overlooked those times of ignorance, he now commands everyone everywhere to repent,
B044C017V031	44	17	31	for he has set a day when he is going to judge the world with justice through a man he has appointed, and he has given proof of this to everyone by raising him from the dead.”
B044C017V032	44	17	32	When they heard about a resurrection of the dead, some began joking about it, while others said, “We will hear you again about this.”
B044C017V033	44	17	33	And so Paul left the meeting.
B044C017V034	44	17	34	Some men joined him and became believers. With them were Dionysius, who was a member of the Areopagus, a woman named Damaris, and some others along with them.
B044C018V001	44	18	1	After this Paul left Athens and went to Corinth.
B044C018V002	44	18	2	There he found a Jew named Aquila, a native of Pontus, who had recently come from Italy with his wife Priscilla because Claudius had ordered all the Jews to leave Rome. Paul went to visit them,
B044C018V003	44	18	3	and because they had the same trade he stayed with them. They worked together because they were tentmakers by trade.
B044C018V004	44	18	4	Every Sabbath he would argue in the synagogue and try to persuade both Jews and Greeks.
B044C018V005	44	18	5	But when Silas and Timothy arrived from Macedonia, Paul devoted himself entirely to the word as he solemnly assured the Jews that Jesus is the Christ.
B044C018V006	44	18	6	But when they began to oppose him and insult him, he shook out his clothes in protest and told them, “Your blood be on your own heads! I am innocent. From now on I will go to the Gentiles.”
B044C018V007	44	18	7	Then he left that place and went to the home of a man named Titius Justus, who worshiped God and whose house was next door to the synagogue.
B044C018V008	44	18	8	Now Crispus, the leader of the synagogue, believed in the Lord, along with his whole family. Many Corinthians who heard Paul also believed and were baptized.
B044C018V009	44	18	9	One night the Lord said to Paul in a vision,
B044C018V010	44	18	10	
        
B044C018V011	44	18	11	So he lived there for a year and a half and continued to teach the word of God among them.
B044C018V012	44	18	12	While Gallio was proconsul of Achaia, the Jews united in an attack on Paul and brought him before the judge's seat.
B044C018V013	44	18	13	They said, “This man is persuading people to worship God in ways that are contrary to the law.”
B044C018V014	44	18	14	Paul was about to open his mouth when Gallio said to the Jews, “If there were some misdemeanor or crime involved, it would be reasonable to put up with you Jews.
B044C018V015	44	18	15	But since it is a question about words, names, and your own law, you will have to take care of that yourselves. I refuse to be a judge in these matters.”
B044C018V016	44	18	16	So he drove them away from the judge's seat.
B044C018V017	44	18	17	Then all of them took Sosthenes, the synagogue leader, and began beating him in front of the judge's seat. But Gallio paid no attention to any of this.
B044C018V018	44	18	18	After staying there for quite a while longer, Paul said goodbye to the brothers and sailed for Syria, accompanied by Priscilla and Aquila. In Cenchraea he had his hair cut, since he was under a vow.
B044C018V019	44	18	19	When they arrived in Ephesus, he left them there. Then he went into the synagogue and had a discussion with the Jews.
B044C018V020	44	18	20	They asked him to stay longer, but he refused.
B044C018V021	44	18	21	As he told them goodbye, he said, “I will come back to you again if it is God's will.” Then he set sail from Ephesus.
B044C018V022	44	18	22	When he arrived in Caesarea, he went up to Jerusalem, greeted the church, and then returned to Antioch.
B044C018V023	44	18	23	After spending some time there, he departed and went from place to place through the region of Galatia and Phrygia, strengthening all the disciples.
B044C018V024	44	18	24	Meanwhile, a Jew named Apollos arrived in Ephesus. He was a native of Alexandria and an eloquent man, one powerful in the Scriptures.
B044C018V025	44	18	25	He had been instructed in the Lord's way, and with spiritual fervor he kept speaking and teaching accurately about Jesus, although he knew only about John's baptism.
B044C018V026	44	18	26	He began to speak boldly in the synagogue, but when Priscilla and Aquila heard him, they took him home and explained God's way to him more accurately.
B044C018V027	44	18	27	When he wanted to cross over to Achaia, the brothers wrote and urged the disciples to welcome him. On his arrival he greatly helped those who through grace had believed.
B044C018V028	44	18	28	He successfully refuted the Jews in public and proved by the Scriptures that Jesus is the Christ.
B044C019V001	44	19	1	It was while Apollos was in Corinth that Paul passed through the inland districts and came to Ephesus. He found a few disciples there
B044C019V002	44	19	2	and asked them, “Did you receive the Holy Spirit when you believed?”They answered him, “No, we haven't even heard that there is a Holy Spirit.”
B044C019V003	44	19	3	He then asked, “Then into what were you baptized?”They answered, “Into John's baptism.”
B044C019V004	44	19	4	Then Paul said, “John baptized with a baptism of repentance, telling the people to believe in the one who was to come after him, that is, in Jesus.”
B044C019V005	44	19	5	On hearing this, they were baptized in the name of the Lord Jesus.
B044C019V006	44	19	6	When Paul laid his hands on them, the Holy Spirit came on them, and they began to speak in tongues and to prophesy.
B044C019V007	44	19	7	There were about twelve men in all.
B044C019V008	44	19	8	He went into the synagogue and spoke there boldly for three months, holding discussions and persuading them about the kingdom of God.
B044C019V009	44	19	9	But when some people became stubborn, refused to believe, and slandered the Way before the people, he left them, took his disciples away from them, and had daily discussions in the lecture hall of Tyrannus.
B044C019V010	44	19	10	This went on for two years, so that all who lived in Asia, Jews and Greeks alike, heard the word of the Lord.
B044C019V011	44	19	11	God continued to do extraordinary miracles by Paul's hands.
B044C019V012	44	19	12	When the handkerchiefs and aprons that had touched his skin were taken to the sick, their diseases left them, and the evil spirits went out of them.
B044C019V013	44	19	13	Then some Jews who went around trying to drive out demons attempted to use the name of the Lord Jesus on those who had evil spirits, saying, “I command you by that Jesus whom Paul preaches!”
B044C019V014	44	19	14	Seven sons of a Jewish high priest named Sceva were doing this.
B044C019V015	44	19	15	But the evil spirit said to them, “I know Jesus, and I am acquainted with Paul, but who are you?”
B044C019V016	44	19	16	Then the man with the evil spirit jumped on them, got the better of them, and so violently overpowered all of them that they fled out of the house naked and bruised.
B044C019V017	44	19	17	When this became known to everyone living in Ephesus, Jews and Greeks alike, fear came on all of them, and the name of the Lord Jesus began to be held in high honor.
B044C019V018	44	19	18	Many who became believers kept coming and confessing and telling about their practices.
B044C019V019	44	19	19	Moreover, many people who had practiced occult arts gathered their books and burned them in front of everybody. They estimated the price of them and found they were worth 50,000 silver coins.
B044C019V020	44	19	20	In that way the word of the Lord kept spreading and triumphing.
B044C019V021	44	19	21	After these things had happened, Paul resolved in the Spirit to go through Macedonia and Achaia and then to go on to Jerusalem, saying, “After I have gone there, I must also see Rome.”
B044C019V022	44	19	22	So he sent two of his helpers, Timothy and Erastus, to Macedonia, while he himself stayed in Asia a while longer.
B044C019V023	44	19	23	Now just about that time a great commotion broke out concerning the Way.
B044C019V024	44	19	24	A silversmith named Demetrius provided a large income for the skilled workers by making silver shrines of Artemis.
B044C019V025	44	19	25	He called a meeting of these men and others who were engaged in similar trades and said, “Men, you well know that we get a good income from this business.
B044C019V026	44	19	26	You also see and hear that, not only in Ephesus, but almost all over Asia, this man Paul has won over and taken away a large crowd by telling them that gods made by human hands are not gods at all.
B044C019V027	44	19	27	There is a danger not only that our business will lose its reputation but also that the temple of the great goddess Artemis will be brought into contempt and that she will be robbed of her majesty that brought all Asia and the world to worship her.”
B044C019V028	44	19	28	When they heard this, they became furious and began to shout, “Great is Artemis of the Ephesians!”
B044C019V029	44	19	29	The city was filled with confusion, and the people rushed into the theater together, dragging with them Gaius and Aristarchus, Paul's fellow travelers from Macedonia.
B044C019V030	44	19	30	Paul wanted to go into the crowd, but the disciples wouldn't let him.
B044C019V031	44	19	31	Even some officials of the province of Asia who were his friends sent him a message urging him not to risk his life in the theater.
B044C019V032	44	19	32	Meanwhile, some were shouting one thing, some another. For the assembly was confused, and most of them didn't know why they were meeting.
B044C019V033	44	19	33	Some of the crowd concluded it was because of Alexander, since the Jews had pushed him to the front. So Alexander motioned for silence and tried to make a defense before the people.
B044C019V034	44	19	34	But when they found out that he was a Jew, they all started to shout in unison for about two hours, “Great is Artemis of the Ephesians!”
B044C019V035	44	19	35	When the city recorder had quieted the crowd, he said, “Men of Ephesus, who in the world doesn't know that this city of Ephesus is the keeper of the temple of the great Artemis and of the statue that fell down from heaven?
B044C019V036	44	19	36	Since these things cannot be denied, you must be quiet and not do anything reckless.
B044C019V037	44	19	37	For you have brought these men here, although they neither rob temples nor blaspheme our goddess.
B044C019V038	44	19	38	So if Demetrius and his workers have a charge against anyone, the courts are open and there are proconsuls. They should accuse one another there.
B044C019V039	44	19	39	But if you want anything else, it must be settled in the regular assembly.
B044C019V040	44	19	40	For we are in danger of being charged with rioting today, and there is no good reason we can give to justify this commotion.”
B044C019V041	44	19	41	After saying this, he dismissed the assembly.
B044C020V001	44	20	1	When the uproar was over, Paul sent for the disciples and encouraged them. Then he said goodbye to them and left to go to Macedonia.
B044C020V002	44	20	2	He went through those regions and encouraged the people with many words. Then he went to Greece
B044C020V003	44	20	3	and stayed there for three months. When he was about to sail for Syria, a plot was made against him by the Jews, so he decided to go back through Macedonia.
B044C020V004	44	20	4	He was accompanied by Sopater (the son of Pyrrhus) from Berea, Aristarchus and Secundus from Thessalonica, Gaius from Derbe, Timothy, and Tychicus and Trophimus from Asia.
B044C020V005	44	20	5	These men went on ahead and were waiting for us in Troas.
B044C020V006	44	20	6	After the days of Unleavened Bread, we sailed from Philippi, and days later we joined them in Troas and stayed there for seven days.
B044C020V007	44	20	7	On the first day of the week, when we had met to break bread, Paul began to address the people. Since he intended to leave the next day, he went on speaking until midnight.
B044C020V008	44	20	8	Now there were many lamps in the upstairs room where we were meeting.
B044C020V009	44	20	9	A young man named Eutychus, who was sitting in a window, began to sink off into a deep sleep as Paul kept speaking longer and longer. Overcome by sleep, he fell down from the third floor and was picked up dead.
B044C020V010	44	20	10	But Paul went down, bent over him, took him into his arms, and said, “Stop being alarmed, for his life is in him.”
B044C020V011	44	20	11	Then he went back upstairs, broke the bread, and ate. He talked with them for a long time, until dawn, and then left.
B044C020V012	44	20	12	Then they took the boy away alive and were greatly relieved.
B044C020V013	44	20	13	We went ahead to the ship and sailed for Assos, where we were intending to pick up Paul. He had arranged it this way, since he had planned to travel there on foot.
B044C020V014	44	20	14	When he met us in Assos, we took him on board and went to Mitylene.
B044C020V015	44	20	15	We sailed from there and on the following day arrived off Chios. The next day we crossed over to Samos and stayed at Trogyllium. The day after that we came to Miletus.
B044C020V016	44	20	16	Paul had decided to sail past Ephesus to avoid spending time in Asia, as he was in a hurry to get to Jerusalem for the day of Pentecost, if that was possible.
B044C020V017	44	20	17	From Miletus he sent messengers to Ephesus to ask the elders of the church to meet with him.
B044C020V018	44	20	18	When they came to him, he said to them, “You know how I lived among you the entire time from the first day I set foot in Asia.
B044C020V019	44	20	19	I served the Lord with all humility, with tears, and with trials that came to me through the plots of the Jews.
B044C020V020	44	20	20	I never shrank from telling you anything that would help you nor from teaching you publicly and from house to house.
B044C020V021	44	20	21	I testified to both Jews and Greeks about repentance toward God and faith toward our Lord Jesus.
B044C020V022	44	20	22	“And now, compelled by the Spirit, I am on my way to Jerusalem, not knowing what will happen to me there,
B044C020V023	44	20	23	except that in town after town the Holy Spirit assures me that imprisonment and suffering are waiting for me.
B044C020V024	44	20	24	But I don't place any value on my life, if only I can finish my race and the ministry that I received from the Lord Jesus of testifying to the gospel of God's grace.
B044C020V025	44	20	25	“Now I know that none of you among whom I traveled preaching the kingdom will ever see my face again.
B044C020V026	44	20	26	I therefore declare to you today that I am not responsible for the blood of any of you,
B044C020V027	44	20	27	for I never shrank from telling you the whole plan of God.
B044C020V028	44	20	28	Pay attention to yourselves and to the entire flock in which the Holy Spirit has made you overseers to be shepherds of God's church, which he acquired with his own blood.
B044C020V029	44	20	29	I know that when I'm gone savage wolves will come among you and not spare the flock.
B044C020V030	44	20	30	Indeed, some of your own men will come forward and distort the truth in order to lure the disciples into following them.
B044C020V031	44	20	31	So be alert! Remember that for three years, night and day, I never stopped warning each of you with tears.
B044C020V032	44	20	32	“I am now entrusting you to God and to the message of his grace, which is able to build you up and give you an inheritance among all who are sanctified.
B044C020V033	44	20	33	I never desired anyone's silver, gold, or clothes.
B044C020V034	44	20	34	You yourselves know that I worked with my own hands to support myself and those who were with me.
B044C020V035	44	20	35	In every way I showed you that by working hard like this we should help the weak and remember the words that the Lord Jesus himself said,
B044C020V036	44	20	36	When he had said this, he knelt down and prayed with all of them.
B044C020V037	44	20	37	All of them cried and cried as they put their arms around Paul and kissed him with affection.
B044C020V038	44	20	38	They were especially sorrowful because of what he had said—that they would never see his face again. Then they took him to the ship.
B044C021V001	44	21	1	When we had torn ourselves away from them, we sailed straight to Cos, and the next day to Rhodes, and from there to Patara.
B044C021V002	44	21	2	There we found a ship going across to Phoenecia, so we went aboard and sailed away.
B044C021V003	44	21	3	We came in sight of Cyprus, and leaving it on our left we sailed on to Syria and landed at Tyre because the ship was to unload its cargo there.
B044C021V004	44	21	4	So we looked up the disciples and stayed there for seven days. Through the Spirit they kept telling Paul not to go to Jerusalem,
B044C021V005	44	21	5	but when our days there were ended we left and proceeded on our journey. All of them with their wives and children accompanied us out of the city. We knelt on the beach, prayed,
B044C021V006	44	21	6	and said goodbye to each other. Then we went aboard the ship, and they went back home.
B044C021V007	44	21	7	On finishing the voyage from Tyre, we arrived at Ptolemais, greeted the brothers, and stayed with them for one day.
B044C021V008	44	21	8	The next day we left and came to Caesarea. We went to the home of Philip the evangelist, one of the seven, and stayed with him.
B044C021V009	44	21	9	He had four unmarried daughters who could prophesy.
B044C021V010	44	21	10	After we had been there for a number of days, a prophet named Agabus arrived from Judea.
B044C021V011	44	21	11	He came to us, took Paul's belt, and tied his own feet and hands with it. Then he said, “The Holy Spirit says, ‘This is how the Jews in Jerusalem will tie up the man who owns this belt. Then they will hand him over to the Gentiles.’”
B044C021V012	44	21	12	When we heard this, we and the people who lived there begged him not to go up to Jerusalem.
B044C021V013	44	21	13	Then Paul replied, “What do you mean by crying and breaking my heart? I'm ready not only to be tied up in Jerusalem but even to die for the name of the Lord Jesus!”
B044C021V014	44	21	14	When he could not be persuaded, we remained silent except to say, “May the Lord's will be done.”
B044C021V015	44	21	15	After those days, we got ready to go up to Jerusalem.
B044C021V016	44	21	16	Some of the disciples from Caesarea went with us. They took us to the home of Mnason to be his guests. He was from Cyprus and had been an early disciple.
B044C021V017	44	21	17	When we arrived in Jerusalem, the brothers welcomed us warmly.
B044C021V018	44	21	18	The next day Paul went with us to visit James, and all the elders were present.
B044C021V019	44	21	19	After greeting them, Paul related one by one the things that God had done among the Gentiles through his ministry.
B044C021V020	44	21	20	When they heard about it, they praised God and told him, “You see, brother, how many thousands of believers there are among the Jews, and all of them are zealous for the law.
B044C021V021	44	21	21	But they have been told about you—that you teach all the Jews living among the Gentiles to forsake the Law of Moses, and that you tell them not to circumcise their children or observe the customs.
B044C021V022	44	21	22	What is to be done? They will certainly hear that you have come.
B044C021V023	44	21	23	So do what we tell you. We have four men who are under a vow.
B044C021V024	44	21	24	Take these men, go through the purification ceremony with them, and pay the expenses to shave their heads. Then everyone will know that there is nothing in what they have been told about you, but that you yourself constantly observe and guard the law.
B044C021V025	44	21	25	As for the Gentiles who have become believers, we have sent a letter with our judgment that they should keep away from food that has been sacrificed to idols, from blood, from the meat of strangled animals, and from sexual immorality.”
B044C021V026	44	21	26	Then Paul took the men and the next day purified himself with them. Then he went into the temple to announce the time when the days of purification would be over and when the sacrifice would be offered for each of them.
B044C021V027	44	21	27	When the seven days were almost over, the Jews from Asia, seeing Paul in the temple, stirred up the whole crowd. They grabbed him,
B044C021V028	44	21	28	yelling, “Men of Israel, help! This is the man who teaches everyone everywhere to turn against our people, the law, and this place. More than that, he has even brought Greeks into the temple and desecrated this holy place.”
B044C021V029	44	21	29	For they had earlier seen Trophimus the Ephesian in the city with him and had supposed that Paul had taken him into the temple.
B044C021V030	44	21	30	The whole city was in chaos, and the people rushed together. They grabbed Paul and dragged him out of the temple, and at once the doors were shut.
B044C021V031	44	21	31	They were trying to kill him when a report reached the tribune of the cohort that all Jerusalem was in an uproar.
B044C021V032	44	21	32	Immediately he took some soldiers and officers and ran down to them. When they saw the tribune and the soldiers, they stopped beating Paul.
B044C021V033	44	21	33	Then the tribune came up, grabbed Paul, and ordered him to be tied up with two chains. He then asked who Paul was and what he had done.
B044C021V034	44	21	34	Some of the crowd shouted this and some that. Since he couldn't learn the facts because of the confusion, he ordered him to be taken into the barracks.
B044C021V035	44	21	35	When Paul got to the steps, he had to be carried by the soldiers because of the violence of the mob.
B044C021V036	44	21	36	The crowd of people kept following him and shouting, “Kill him!”
B044C021V037	44	21	37	Just as Paul was about to be taken into the barracks, he said to the tribune, “May I say something to you?”He asked, “Do you know Greek?
B044C021V038	44	21	38	You're not the Egyptian who started a revolt some time ago and led 4,000 assassins into the desert, are you?”
B044C021V039	44	21	39	Paul replied, “I am a Jew from Tarsus in Cilicia, a citizen of no insignificant city. I beg you to let me speak to the people.”
B044C021V040	44	21	40	He gave him permission, and Paul, standing on the steps, motioned with his hand for the people to be silent. When everyone had quieted down, he spoke to them in the Hebrew language.
B044C022V001	44	22	1	“Brothers and fathers, listen to the defense that I am now making before you.”
B044C022V002	44	22	2	When they heard him speaking to them in Hebrew, they became even more quiet, and he continued,
B044C022V003	44	22	3	“I am a Jew, born in Tarsus in Cilicia but raised in this city and educated at the feet of Gamaliel in the strict ways of our ancestral law. I am as zealous for God as all of you are today.
B044C022V004	44	22	4	I persecuted this Way even to the death and kept tying up both men and women and putting them in prison,
B044C022V005	44	22	5	as the high priest and the whole Council of elders can testify about me. From them I also received letters to the brothers in Damascus, and I was going there to tie up those who were there and bring them back to Jerusalem to be punished.
B044C022V006	44	22	6	“But while I was on my way and approaching Damascus about noon, a bright light from heaven suddenly flashed around me.
B044C022V007	44	22	7	I fell to the ground and heard a voice saying to me,
B044C022V008	44	22	8	I answered, ‘Who are you, Lord?’ He said to me,
B044C022V009	44	22	9	The men who were with me saw the light but didn't understand the voice of the one who was speaking to me.
B044C022V010	44	22	10	“Then I asked, ‘What am I to do, Lord?’ The Lord told me,
B044C022V011	44	22	11	Since I could not see because of the brightness of the light, the men who were with me took me by the hand and led me into Damascus.
B044C022V012	44	22	12	“A certain Ananias, who was a devout man in accordance with the law and who was highly regarded by all the Jews living there,
B044C022V013	44	22	13	came to me. He stood beside me and said, ‘Brother Saul, receive your sight!’ At that moment I could see him.
B044C022V014	44	22	14	Then he said, ‘The God of our ancestors has chosen you to know his will, to see the Righteous One, and to hear his own voice,
B044C022V015	44	22	15	because you will be his witness to all people of what you have seen and heard.
B044C022V016	44	22	16	What are you waiting for now? Get up, be baptized, and have your sins washed away as you call on his name.’
B044C022V017	44	22	17	“Then I returned to Jerusalem. While I was praying in the temple, I fell into a trance
B044C022V018	44	22	18	and saw the Lord saying to me,
B044C022V019	44	22	19	I said, ‘Lord, they themselves know that in every synagogue I kept imprisoning and beating those who believe in you.
B044C022V020	44	22	20	Even when the blood of your witness Stephen was being shed, I was standing there approving it and guarding the coats of those who were killing him.’
B044C022V021	44	22	21	Then he said to me,
